1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] Okay ladies and gentlemen,I would like first of all to express my gratitude to be here,to the organizers of this conference and also to the faculty and his deacon for their hospitality.The topic of my discussion today,or better to say the topic of my lecture is,as you already heard,the relationships between East and West from 5th to 15th century.And it's actually quite wide.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:01:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] a topic that goes for almost one millennia,but I will try to be short and I will try to point out some of the most important historical events that shaped,as we already heard from Professor Vedrish,this entire story of schism between East and West,which was of course much much deeper than one thing that happened in 1054.So I would like to begin this lecture of mine with one simple definition.

3
00:01:00,000 --> 00:01:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] and that is my definition of East and West.When we talk about East and West,I would like to talk about the Western and Eastern part of what we used to know as the Roman Empire.So Eastern Roman Empire and the Western Roman Empire.

4
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] Of course,I believe that many of you know,that the very term Byzantium is actually something that is created,well,rather late in our common history from 16th to 18th century.

5
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] that term Byzantium is a derogatory term basically for what used to be the Eastern Roman Empire for a very simple reason.The European historians who essentially created this new world view of history that we have today.

6
00:01:39,000 --> 00:02:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] whether it be Edward Gibbon or Hieronymus Wolf,both both of them considered what we see as the Eastern Roman Empire,especially during the Middle Ages,as something that is not Latin,that is Greek,that is not Catholic,that is Orthodox,and at the same time something that culturally doesn't have anything in common with Rome,as they saw it,but has more in common with oriental traditions,language literature and so on.

7
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] And I would prefer to use the Eastern Roman Empire to make clear what I want to say in this lecture.

8
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] So let's begin from the 5th century and from the fall of the Western Roman Empire.

9
00:02:18,000 --> 00:02:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now basically what happened then,and I didn't want to use any kind of maps,you just have to imagine the map of Europe.

10
00:02:25,000 --> 00:02:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] So when we talk about the 5th century what we essentially have is the fall of the Western Roman Empire.

11
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] Some historians even up to today say that it wasn't really a fall,it was more like a transformation of the Roman Empire.

12
00:02:38,000 --> 00:02:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] So you can think about it whatever you want,but I think it's more about the fall of civilization,not just the fall of one imperial administration.

13
00:02:45,000 --> 00:02:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] What basically happens is that in a political sense the Western part of the Roman Empire is overrun by different nations.

14
00:02:53,000 --> 00:03:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] We will call them barbarian groups,most of them Germans like Goths,Vandals,Francs and so on.

15
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] And what happens there is that in this beginning of the 5th century,well at the end of the 5th century,we essentially see for the first time the theory of the Eastern Roman Empire.

16
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] Their political world view.

17
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now it's very important to understand one thing,those barbarians who entered the Roman Empire,most of them didn't really want to destroy the Roman Empire.

18
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] They are most likely something like the refugees or,you want to call them some other name of course,the people who are coming today in Europe.

19
00:03:34,000 --> 00:03:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] They want to be part of something that is great,that is big and that is presumably rich.

20
00:03:39,000 --> 00:03:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] So the barbarians from the north wanted to enter the Roman Empire and they did and in the process they kind of,you know,they didn't destroy the Roman Empire.

21
00:03:48,000 --> 00:03:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] They were not the cause of its fall,but they were there as one very important reason.

22
00:03:54,000 --> 00:04:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] So what happens there is that the Eastern Roman Empire decides to try to get hold of the West the best way possible

23
00:04:01,000 --> 00:04:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] and they do it by giving entire new honorary titles to these barbarian rulers in the West.

24
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] For example in the 6th century a Frankish King Clovis after his win over the Alemanni tribe at the modern day in Germany was given an honorary title of Roman council.

25
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] This was something that the Roman law would not acknowledge but we see at this day and age that the Eastern Roman Empire

26
00:04:28,000 --> 00:04:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] essentially is trying to play its power on the West like nothing happened.

27
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] They essentially see the entirety of the Roman Empire East and West as part of one single Imperium Romanum.

28
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] And they will essentially up until the end,the end of the East Roman Empire, the fall of Constantinople in 1453,

29
00:04:51,000 --> 00:04:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] they will see the West as nothing more than the part of the Roman Empire that is essentially going to become a Roman Empire.

30
00:04:57,000 --> 00:05:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] once more. They saw the Roman Empire from the Byzantine, from the East Roman perspective as basically, how should I say,

31
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:16,000
[SPEAKER_00] a kingdom of God on earth with one church, one religion and one emperor, of course,

32
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] and that true emperor was the emperor in the East.

33
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] One great problem for this theory and try to put it into practice was that Byzantines or the East Romans could not effectively put any type of control in the West.

34
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] They tried a couple of times but they failed.

35
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] The most notable attempt to put this theory into practice was the reconquista of Emperor Justinian in the early 6th century when he essentially tried to conquer, again reconquer, retake the Western part of the Roman Empire

36
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:52,000
[SPEAKER_00] and he was willing to do anything, spend anything to reunite the Empire.

37
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:58,000
[SPEAKER_00] And he went on a series of wars against the Vandals in North Africa, against the Ostrogoths in Italy.

38
00:05:58,000 --> 00:06:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] But after all of that, he managed to take parts of Italy, parts of North Africa, parts of Spain, but essentially, it was too much for Eastern Roman Empire army to take.

39
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] And after that, basically, his successors are turned to the East.

40
00:06:14,000 --> 00:06:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] And now basically from 7th century onwards, we see the shift in which the Byzantines or the Eastern Roman emperors turned to the East.

41
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:31,000
[SPEAKER_00] And from the, I would say, from the 8th century and the rule of Emperor Heraclius, the Greek language becomes the official language of the Empire.

42
00:06:31,000 --> 00:06:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] So it's Greek, not Latin.

43
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:38,000
[SPEAKER_00] And this entire cultural shift to what we know as Byzantium has started.

44
00:06:38,000 --> 00:06:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] At the same time, so we will have, during the entire history of Western and Eastern relationship, we will kind of have two problems.

45
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] First will be, we could say, on a level of theological doctrine and of the supremacy between the bishop in Rome,

46
00:06:57,000 --> 00:07:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] the person that we call Pope, and, of course, the emperor in the East.

47
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, what is very important to understand, during the entirety of the Byzantine Empire or the Eastern Roman Empire,

48
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:13,000
[SPEAKER_00] they considered Pope to be nothing more than just one of the five patriarchs.

49
00:07:13,000 --> 00:07:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] One of them was supposed to be in Constantinople, the second in Rome, the third in Jerusalem, the fourth in Alexandria, and the fifth in Antioch.

50
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] So he was supposed to be like primus inter pares.

51
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] But I would say, and I would just gloss over it, one of the reasons why papacy was so important in the Christian West from the 8th century onwards,

52
00:07:33,000 --> 00:07:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] was because the church, the Roman church, was probably the only institution that survived the fall of the Western Roman Empire.

53
00:07:41,000 --> 00:07:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] And the bishop of Rome also was duke of the duchy of Rome.

54
00:07:47,000 --> 00:07:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] He also had a large political meaning.

55
00:07:50,000 --> 00:07:59,000
[SPEAKER_00] But, of course, the Byzantines saw all that as nonsense, and they believed that only Byzantine emperor is the sole appointed of God on earth,

56
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] and that he has the rule over land, sea, and religion in the entirety of the Roman Empire.

57
00:08:05,000 --> 00:08:11,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, I would just gloss a little bit faster over some important topics.

58
00:08:11,000 --> 00:08:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, the first major problem with this happened in the late 8th and early 9th century,

59
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:23,000
[SPEAKER_00] when the Roman Empire in the West was restored, formally restored, in the image of Charlemagne, the Frankish king,

60
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] who essentially became a new Roman emperor.

61
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, in his worldview, the Roman Empire in the West was re-established.

62
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] Of course, the Byzantines didn't take that very lightly.

63
00:08:32,000 --> 00:08:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] There was a war with the Charlemagne, but it also proved, again, one major problem for the Byzantines,

64
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] and that's the fact that they simply cannot, because of the geographical terms and the military strength,

65
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] they cannot really control the West.

66
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, what basically happens there, after the war, with the Treaty of Aachen,

67
00:08:51,000 --> 00:09:01,000
[SPEAKER_00] they decided to give Charlemagne the title of emperor, but the title of emperor in nothing more than abstract sense.

68
00:09:01,000 --> 00:09:05,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, he's an emperor, but he's not the emperor of Romans, he's just an emperor.

69
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] And this is very common practice for the East Roman Empire,

70
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] as they simply cannot deal with the fact that they cannot rule the West and the East altogether,

71
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] so they come up with all these different names, all these different titles that actually shouldn't exist in law.

72
00:09:22,000 --> 00:09:32,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, what happens after that, we have the first great schism, before the great schism of 1024,

73
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] and that is the iconoclastic struggle in the 8th century, when East Roman Emperor Leo decides to proclaim icons,

74
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] which are basically two-dimensional images showing the life of Jesus Christ and the pictures from the Holy Scripture,

75
00:09:47,000 --> 00:09:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] he decided to say that those icons are exceptionally heretic, because the idea was if you pray to icon,

76
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] you're not praying to God, you're praying to a material thing.

77
00:09:57,000 --> 00:10:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] Of course, the Pope was against it, and then we have the first major theological strife between the doctrine of the emperor and the Pope.

78
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] After that, of course, we have another problem.

79
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] In the 10th century, we have another Roman Empire created in the West, and that is the German Roman Empire of Otto I.

80
00:10:17,000 --> 00:10:28,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, this was much more dangerous for the Byzantines, because Otto I actually claimed that he has the Roman origin of his imperial right to rule.

81
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:41,000
[SPEAKER_00] I will not get into details on this, but this was another proof that the Byzantines actually cannot rule in any shape or any term with the West.

82
00:10:41,000 --> 00:10:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] I'll just point out one thing when we talk about these different titles that the Byzantines would give to the Western leaders.

83
00:10:48,000 --> 00:10:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] We have one such example from our own history, Croatian history, in the 10th century when the first Croatian king, Tomislav,

84
00:10:55,000 --> 00:11:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] sends a letter to the Pope, and he is ascribed as Tomislav Rex Curatorum, the king of the Croats.

85
00:11:02,000 --> 00:11:07,000
[SPEAKER_00] The Pope, essentially, sends the letter back titled, "To Tomislav, king of the Croats."

86
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:14,000
[SPEAKER_00] But when he says the same letter to the Byzantine emperor in the East, he is not proclaimed a king,

87
00:11:14,000 --> 00:11:20,000
[SPEAKER_00] but the Byzantines give him a title which they think he deserves, and they call him Archont Tomislav.

88
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] What Archont actually means, we're not sure, probably some kind of ruler that rules Biden, at least by some kind of spiritual guidance from the Byzantines.

89
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] They just want to have some kind of influence over the West, if nothing, then just in words.

90
00:11:35,000 --> 00:11:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] Then we come to 11th century and to the Great Schism, which is the topic of this whole conference, and I will not speak much about it.

91
00:11:43,000 --> 00:11:49,000
[SPEAKER_00] I will just say that we have some major differences that contributed to that.

92
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:54,000
[SPEAKER_00] Those differences are theological, political, and cultural.

93
00:11:54,000 --> 00:12:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] There is, of course, the question of papal authority, the filioque clause of the Nassian Creed.

94
00:12:00,000 --> 00:12:02,000
[SPEAKER_00] I believe many of you know what it is.

95
00:12:02,000 --> 00:12:06,000
[SPEAKER_00] It's basically the idea that the Holy Spirit derives from Father and the Son.

96
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] Filioque means "and the Son."

97
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] While in the original Nassian Creed of 325, the idea was that the Holy Spirit comes only from the Father.

98
00:12:15,000 --> 00:12:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] This may seem as an unimportant distinction to us today, but for the people in the 10th and 11th century, it was of supreme importance.

99
00:12:25,000 --> 00:12:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] Then we have, of course, the different rhetorical practices, the question of celibacy, and all of that leads to the confrontation of basically two people.

100
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:47,000
[SPEAKER_00] We have the patriarch of Constantinople and the Pope's ambassador, Humbert, and then we have what is known as the Great Schism, about which you will hear more during this session.

101
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] And now I simply want to point out the remaining and the most important, I would say, part in this relationship between East and West, which were going from bad to worse.

102
00:12:57,000 --> 00:13:12,000
[SPEAKER_00] From the end of the 11th to the 15th century, we have one major factor that essentially contributes to the fall of the East and the total destruction of any kind of rational relationships between East and West, and that is the Crusades.

103
00:13:12,000 --> 00:13:17,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, the Crusades started at the end of the 11th century when Byzantine Emperor actually asked for help in the West.

104
00:13:17,000 --> 00:13:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] And he doesn't ask the Emperor, he doesn't ask any king, he has the Pope himself, first Pope Gregory and then Pope Urban.

105
00:13:25,000 --> 00:13:40,000
[SPEAKER_00] And in 1095, we have the beginning of the First Crusade, the Crusade which tore down what was left of some kind of idea that East and West could become united again.

106
00:13:40,000 --> 00:13:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] Because there is always, when East needs help from the West, there is always this notion that if you help us, there could be some kind of reconciliation.

107
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:53,000
[SPEAKER_00] It, of course, will never happen because most of these claims were just political, they were not sincere.

108
00:13:53,000 --> 00:13:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] So what happens there and we have, of course, the most important Fourth Crusade.

109
00:13:57,000 --> 00:14:08,000
[SPEAKER_00] Now, the giant crusading army, mostly assembled in France on the Venetian fleet, went to, I mean their goal, the goal of this crusading army was Egypt and then the Holy Land.

110
00:14:08,000 --> 00:14:15,000
[SPEAKER_00] It ended up conquering and plundering two Christian cities, first Zadar and then Constantinople in 1204.

111
00:14:15,000 --> 00:14:22,000
[SPEAKER_00] After this, the Latin Empire was established on what was supposed to be the Eastern Roman Empire.

112
00:14:22,000 --> 00:14:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] But the Byzantine Empire was restored in 1265 by the new dynasty, the dynasty of Paleologoi, which will, of course, be the last dynasty of the Byzantine Empire.

113
00:14:33,000 --> 00:14:45,000
[SPEAKER_00] What happens there is essentially the rebirth of the Byzantine Empire, of East Roman Empire, but it is extremely weak and it essentially never recovered from what happened to it in 1204.

114
00:14:45,000 --> 00:15:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] From this circle of Constantinople in 1204, I will just give you one data and it comes from the words of Geoffrey de Velaruddin, who was essentially the commander of the Fourth Crusade.

115
00:15:00,000 --> 00:15:21,000
[SPEAKER_00] He said that the estimated loot from Constantinople itself was 1400,000 silver marks, which is essentially triple the amount of silver that the Frankish or French king would get in one year for his royal household.

116
00:15:21,000 --> 00:15:29,000
[SPEAKER_00] And what we essentially have from the 12th to the 15th century is the fall of power in the East.

117
00:15:29,000 --> 00:15:33,000
[SPEAKER_00] The East is becoming even more weaker and weaker by the day.

118
00:15:33,000 --> 00:15:46,000
[SPEAKER_00] And also, at the same time, we have really strong attitude in the West of hatred and blatant hostility towards the East because of the religious and cultural differences.

119
00:15:46,000 --> 00:15:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] And also, at the same time, from the Byzantine point of view, we have a sense of distrust and in some period, also incredible pride.

120
00:15:55,000 --> 00:16:00,000
[SPEAKER_00] They became, they stayed full of their pride until the very end.

121
00:16:00,000 --> 00:16:10,000
[SPEAKER_00] And basically, they called themselves Romans until the 29th of May, 1455, when the Turkish army essentially conquered Constantinople.

122
00:16:10,000 --> 00:16:24,000
[SPEAKER_00] So basically, what I would like to say is not just from theological differences or philosophical differences, but also from the fact that if we look the world in a realpolitik worldview,

123
00:16:24,000 --> 00:16:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] which I think is something that existed through all of history and is not just something that is created by Henry Kissinger,

124
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:39,000
[SPEAKER_00] I would say that if we look the world in that sense, one thing that is very important to have in mind is that the realpolitik looks the world in a kind of pyramid of power.

125
00:16:39,000 --> 00:16:48,000
[SPEAKER_00] And the reason why West didn't really care about the Byzantine Empire and the Eastern Empire from the 12th to 15th century is because it was a very weak empire indeed.

126
00:16:48,000 --> 00:16:51,000
[SPEAKER_00] And it wasn't very important.

127
00:16:51,000 --> 00:17:03,000
[SPEAKER_00] And for that reason alone, the only possible explanation for some peoples in the West why they should help the Eastern Roman Empire was because it was protecting Europe from the Turks.

128
00:17:03,000 --> 00:17:19,000
[SPEAKER_00] But even that didn't work out. We already heard in the previous lecture, and that will be my final say on this, that there were actually two attempts to bring this divide to an end.

129
00:17:19,000 --> 00:17:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] And the final one was at the Council of Florence in 4039.

130
00:17:25,000 --> 00:17:34,000
[SPEAKER_00] And in the Council of Florence, basically, the Eastern Roman Emperor was willing to give up his faith and to basically reunite with the Western Church.

131
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:44,000
[SPEAKER_00] As one Cardinal said, Cardinal Bessarion said of that, he said, "The Greeks have surrendered everything. The only thing left is to obey us."

132
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:50,000
[SPEAKER_00] And it was completely, I mean, moral fall of the Eastern Roman Empire.

133
00:17:50,000 --> 00:17:55,000
[SPEAKER_00] And it ended when Turks conquered the city in 1953.

134
00:17:55,000 --> 00:18:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] One thing that I wanted to point out is how big this stride was between East and West is that many intellectuals in the East believed that the conquest of Constantinople by the Turks is essentially a God's will.

135
00:18:09,000 --> 00:18:26,000
[SPEAKER_00] And so, in his almighty wisdom saved the Orthodox Church and saved the Orthodox faith with allowing this Mohammedan king to come and to conquer the holy city, the legendary city of Constantinople.

136
00:18:26,000 --> 00:18:35,000
[SPEAKER_00] And it's very interesting, all those ancient cities of all those eras, they were perceived as female.

137
00:18:35,000 --> 00:18:43,000
[SPEAKER_00] So Constantinople was called the queen of the cities, Rome was called Roma, like a great mother, mother of love, and et cetera.

138
00:18:43,000 --> 00:18:57,000
[SPEAKER_00] So, to come to an end of this lecture, and I would just like to give kind of my analysis or my idea what we should do with all of this, starting with this conference today, possibly.

139
00:18:57,000 --> 00:19:09,000
[SPEAKER_00] We need the proper and honest dialogue, and we need a reconciliation with our history, because as a history teacher, as a history professor, I know that too often our history divides us.

140
00:19:09,000 --> 00:19:18,000
[SPEAKER_00] But it's because we cannot reach the simple reconciliation between ourselves and inside ourselves of these great stories and great narratives of history.

141
00:19:18,000 --> 00:19:25,000
[SPEAKER_00] And I hope that maybe this conference can be the beginning of something as important as that.

142
00:19:25,000 --> 00:19:30,000
[SPEAKER_00] Thank you very much.

